results.notes: In Saanich BC, Cordova Bay, near the ocean (by a 1/2 block). Growing in a small loose scattered grouping in the grass, some are singular. Small, approximately 1 inch or less, a striking deep wine coloured cap, almost looks like velvet but is smooth to touch. It is slightly umbonate in the centre. Thin flesh. Growing close by: a mountain ash stump (cut four years ago), a grape vine, mint, flowers, an old cherry tree, and two young cherry trees. Cedar hedging. 30 feet away, stump from paper birch. Moss areas mixed in. Gets partial sun. The yard has east to west exposure. The spore print is a red brown. The gills are a lighter wine colour and some are decurrent. The stipe is fragile and not thick or dense. No veil visible. No volva. The smell is hard to detect. This is the second year I have seen them. I’ve added photos of another group of mushrooms growing 2 feet away and more proximal to the ash stump. The red mushrooms are right on the border of the garden bed. The nearest major plant to them is a grapevine.

results.notes:
Collected near the Indian Pass trail. Growing abundantly in leaf and needle litter near Thuja occidentalis, Abies balsamea, Pinus sp., Picea sp., Betula alleghaniensis, Betula papyrifera and Ilex mucronata. Caps convex to pulvinate and centrally depressed to umbilicate; light gray (5Y 7/1 to 5Y 7/2 in Munsell) when fresh; hygrophanous and fading to white (2.5Y 8/2 in Munsell); translucent-striate; viscid; 4.5 to 9.6 mm wide and 2.1 to 5.2 mm tall. Stems light gray (5Y 7/2 in Munsell); viscid; even; hollow; not releasing liquid when cut; 20.6 to 38.6 mm long and 0.8 to 1.3 mm wide; with white basal mycelium. Odor and taste not distintive. Clamps present in the pileipellis. Pileipellis hyphae smooth. Lamellar trama vinescent in Melzer’s reagent. Pleurocystidia absent. Cheilocystidia forming a sterile margin; many in fascicles; hyaline; smooth or irregularly knobby. Cheilocystidia measurements: (31.1) 31.9 – 39.1 (43.6) × (5.3) 5.34 – 7.1 (7.5) µm, Q = (4.6) 5.2 – 6.7 (8.2); N = 9, Me = 36.6 × 6 µm; Qe = 6.1. Basidia 4-sterigmate. Spore print white. results.notes: Observed this flush of white-capped mushrooms for a fews days prior to collection on 9/27/21 thinking they were Agaricus. They were growing on a strip of mowed lawn about about 50 feet from a mature pin oak adjacent to a parking lot. Upon collection, could see they were white Amanitas, possibly A. bisporigera though I’ve never collected this mushroom growing in a dense group like this, generally they seem to be single examples. The dried cap was negative to KOH (see comparison with dried cap of bona fide A. bisporigera). Also, the smell of the fresh mushrooms was foul, as was a earlier collection from this site (OBS 463270). Finally, the dried color of these mushrooms was a pale orange compared to the yellow-white of A. bisporigera. I’ve seen report of a white Amanita that had “apricot colored” gills upon drying but I can’t recall the source. In any case, seems an unusual find to me and I would appreciate any help with better identification.

This single robust immature specimen was not collected at the NJMA foray but brought in by two hikers who happened to stop by because they were curious about the array of fungi displayed at the ID tables. They said they found it “something like 5 miles away”.

Indeed, the odor emanating from this mushroom was similar to the curry odor of the senbilis and the two looked very similar (see photo). The difference became apparent when I cut the two mushrooms: the slightly and erratically bluing flesh is more consistent with pallidorosea, which often doesn’t stain at all.
